   =20
      Buy stocks on Twitter
   =20
 =20

At the height of meme stock mania in early 2021, the WallStreetBets forum o=
n Reddit was   adding a million users a day as people flocked to Reddit to =
discuss their plans to trade GameStop Corp. and other meme stocks. Imagine =
if Reddit put a button next to each GameStop post saying =E2=80=9Cbuy GME,=
=E2=80=9D and if you clicked the button you could buy shares directly throu=
gh Reddit? (I guess maybe add another button like =E2=80=9CYOLO GME options=
=E2=80=9D so you could buy the call options too?) That just seems like it w=
ould be good business, and good customer service, each in a loose approxima=
te way. Probably some compliance issues with that button. Probably some cus=
tomers would be sad if they bought GameStop for $400 with one click after r=
eading an enthusiastic but inaccurate Reddit post. Probably some lawsuits. =
Still the basic business idea =E2=80=94=C2=A0=E2=80=9Cthe place where peopl=
e go to enthusiastically discuss stocks should also let them buy those stoc=
ks directly=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94=C2=A0has an appeal.
Anyway!

Twitter will let its users access stocks, cryptocurrencies and other financ=
ial assets through a partnership with eToro, a social trading company.
Starting Thursday, a new feature will be rolled out on the Twitter app. It =
will allow users to view market charts on an expanded range of financial in=
struments and buy and sell stocks and other assets from eToro, the company =
told CNBC exclusively.
Currently, it=E2=80=99s already possible to view real-time trading data fro=
m TradingView on index funds like the S&P 500 and shares of some companies =
such as Tesla. That can be done using Twitter=E2=80=99s =E2=80=9Ccashtags=
=E2=80=9D feature =E2=80=94 you search for a ticker symbol and insert dolla=
r sign in front of it, after which the app will show you price information =
from TradingView using an API (application programming interface).
With the eToro partnership, Twitter cashtags will be expanded to cover far =
more instruments and asset classes, an eToro spokesperson told CNBC.
You=E2=80=99ll also be able to click a button that says =E2=80=9Cview on eT=
oro,=E2=80=9D which takes you through to eToro=E2=80=99s site, and then buy=
 and sell assets on its platform. EToro uses TradingView as its market data=
 partner.

This is apparently part of Elon Musk=E2=80=99s plan to turn Twitter into a =
=E2=80=9Csuper app=E2=80=9D that offers payments and=C2=A0banking. The enti=
ty formerly known as Twitter Inc. now seems to be named X Corp.,=C2=A0reviv=
ing the name of Musk=E2=80=99s early online bank that eventually became par=
t of PayPal. People like to discuss stocks on Twitter, and Musk wants Twitt=
er/X to get into financial services, and so, sure, connect the stock discus=
sion more closely to a stock brokerage.
This seems fairly tame. But wouldn=E2=80=99t it be great if you could read =
a tweet touting a stock and Twitter would serve you a button saying =E2=80=
=9Cbuy 100 shares of this stock=E2=80=9D and you=E2=80=99d click and Jane S=
treet would sell you the stock and Twitter would get a fee for making it ha=
ppen?
  [1]
=C2=A0Or if   Elon Musk tweeted =E2=80=9CUse Signal,=E2=80=9D there=E2=80=
=99d be a button saying =E2=80=9CBuy Signal,=E2=80=9D and you could buy the=
 stock of Signal Advance Inc., a company that has nothing to do with what M=
usk was tweeting about but which does have the word =E2=80=9CSignal=E2=80=
=9D in its name. Or if Musk  tweeted =E2=80=9CX,=E2=80=9D as he did the oth=
er day, there=E2=80=99d be a button saying =E2=80=9CBuy X,=E2=80=9D and you=
 could click it and buy shares of United States Steel Corp.,   whose ticker=
 is X. Would people click those buttons? I mean, yes, right? Why shouldn=E2=
=80=99t Twitter monetize the=20
Elon Markets Hypothesis?=C2=A0How much would Jane Street pay for those orde=
rs? Those orders seem fun.
  [2]

I said above that there are some compliance issues with that button, but th=
at is the real=C2=A0beauty of this idea:
=09Elon Musk generally seems a bit aggressive on compliance matters, and in=
 particular he does not care at all about securities law compliance. =E2=80=
=9CI want to be clear. I do not respect the SEC. I do not respect them,=E2=
=80=9D   he once said, on television, and that=E2=80=99s one of the  nicer =
things he has said about the US Securities and Exchange Commission. If Elon=
 Musk tells Twitter=E2=80=99s engineers =E2=80=9Cput a button on the site t=
hat lets people buy stock in companies that I tweet about, or in companies =
that have names that are similar to words that I tweet,=E2=80=9D and a lawy=
er pipes up to say =E2=80=9Cthe SEC might have some concerns about that,=E2=
=80=9D he will scream expletives and tell them to make the button bigger. T=
his is not how the leaders of most retail stock brokerages think about thei=
r relationship with the SEC, and it gives Musk certain, uh, competitive adv=
antages.=09The SEC has been burned before and seems to be afraid to   enfor=
ce securities laws against Musk?

I think a lot of people could offer a more seamless and convenient retail s=
tock trading experience if they did not care about, and were not subject to=
,=C2=A0securities regulation.
  [3]
=C2=A0Why not Twitter?
Also, everything I said above, but 10 times more so, for trading=C2=A0crypt=
o=C2=A0on Twitter. As is true for a lot of people on Twitter,  including El=
on Musk, a great deal of my feed consists of typo-filled spam trying to con=
vince me to send my money to some sort of crypto scam. Imagine if I could d=
o that directly in the app! So convenient!

