   =20
      Bribes
   =20
 =20

A  running theme of this column, which is never legal advice, is that if yo=
u are going to do bribes you should try to be businesslike about your bribe=
s, instead of being cutesy. Like if you send your colleague a text message =
saying =E2=80=9Cour =E2=80=98friend=E2=80=99 expects one million =E2=80=98c=
hickens=E2=80=99 for his =E2=80=98help=E2=80=99 with this =E2=80=98contract=
,=E2=80=99=E2=80=9D that=E2=80=99s gonna look really bad to the jury at you=
r inevitable criminal trial. But if you send a professionally formatted=C2=
=A0invoice saying, like, =E2=80=9CConsulting charges: 80 hours @ $1,250 per=
 hour plus 45 basis point success fee on $200 million contract =3D $1,000,0=
00 to be paid by ACH transfer to General Consulting Services LLC,=E2=80=9D =
you might still get arrested, but at trial you can say =E2=80=9Cno that was=
 for consulting, very standard, nothing wrong with that.=E2=80=9D
Yesterday US prosecutors brought bribery charges against 10 people =E2=80=
=9Cin connection with a massive scheme to defraud Polar Air Cargo Worldwide=
, Inc. (=E2=80=98Polar=E2=80=99), a leading cargo airline, of tens of milli=
ons of dollars=E2=80=9D with bribes. Polar is a cargo airline =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0a joint venture of DHL and Atlas Air =E2=80=94=C2=A0that sold cargo spac=
e to shippers, and if you wanted cargo space on Polar you allegedly had to =
pay (1) Polar the rates that it charged you plus (2) some bribes to the Pol=
ar executives who were selling you the space.=C2=A0
The executives included Polar=E2=80=99s chief operating officer, its vice p=
resident of marketing,=C2=A0its vice president of operations and its senior=
 director of customer service. =E2=80=9CIn general,=E2=80=9D says the indic=
tment,=C2=A0=E2=80=9Cthe=C2=A0Executive Defendants often had the ability to=
 propose vendors, to advocate on behalf of certain vendors or customers, an=
d to exercise significant influence over both Polar's selection of vendors =
and the rates offered to its customers.=E2=80=9D They were the people selli=
ng space on Polar=E2=80=99s planes, and so they could set the rates for tha=
t space =E2=80=94=C2=A0and the rates they set, allegedly, included both a p=
ayment to Polar and a payment to themselves.
But it was all businesslike. From the indictment:

To conceal the kickbacks and conflicted ownership interests from Polar, and=
 thereby to continue the fraud scheme, [they]=C2=A0often directed the kickb=
acks and ownership distributions be paid to limited liability companies wit=
h non-descript names that were, in fact, controlled by the Executive Defend=
ants. =E2=80=A6
From in or about 2009 through in or about July 2021, Polar contracted with =
freight forwarders to sell available cargo space on behalf of downstream sh=
ipping customers, who, in turn, paid freight forwarders to secure cargo spa=
ce and coordinate logistics. ... These kickbacks were typically calculated =
based on how many kilograms of cargo the freight forwarders had shipped wit=
h Polar during a particular period. At no point before the discovery of the=
 fraud in or about July 2021 were the kickbacks from freight forwarders kno=
wn to Polar.

=E2=80=9CAt no point =E2=80=A6=C2=A0were the kickbacks from freight forward=
ers known to Polar=E2=80=9D is a weird sentence. Polar is not a person; it =
has no consciousness. The kickbacks were not known to Polar=E2=80=99s=C2=A0=
owners, I assume, or perhaps to its chief executive officer. But they were =
known to its chief operating officer, because he was allegedly receiving th=
em. This was not some rogue salesperson taking bribes; this was a big chunk=
 of the executive team.
And so there is an amazing civil lawsuit filed late last year by one of the=
 customers, Cargo On Demand Inc., against Polar, complaining that Polar cha=
rged it bribes. Cargo On Demand=E2=80=99s point was, look, if Polar=E2=80=
=99s salespeople and senior managers told it to pay these fees as part of t=
he price of cargo, it had to pay those fees. From the complaint:

COD entered into the [Blokced Space Agreement] with Polar primarily because=
 Polar=E2=80=99s rates on the specific air routes relevant to COD=E2=80=99s=
 customers were typically lower than the rates quoted to COD by any other a=
irlines providing service on the same routes.
However, in order to actually utilize its cargo space allotment, COD was ad=
vised by members of Polar Management that it was required to also pay Polar=
 (via Polar Management), and certain third-party consulting companies conne=
cted to Polar, additional =E2=80=9Cconsulting fees=E2=80=9D separate and ap=
art from the BSA.
These consulting fees were charged beginning at the inception of COD=E2=80=
=99s relationship with Polar in 2014. =E2=80=A6
The consulting fees were calculated based on the monthly tonnage for all go=
ods that COD shipped with Polar. The amount of the fee typically varied bet=
ween $0.25-$0.50 per kilo of tonnage, in addition to the agreed BSA rates.
The consulting fee requirement was articulated to COD by multiple members o=
f Polar Management (which included, without limitation, the company=E2=80=
=99s Chief Operating Officer and multiple vice presidents and directors) ov=
er the course of seven years. =E2=80=A6
COD was advised and instructed by Polar Management that these additional =
=E2=80=9Cconsulting fees=E2=80=9D were part of Polar=E2=80=99s regular way =
of doing business with all customers that had annual BSA contracts with Pol=
ar.
To COD, such fees seemed akin to a hotel =E2=80=9Cresort fee=E2=80=9D. In o=
ther words, a mandatory fee that is not included (or not prominently includ=
ed) in the quoted rate, yet mandatorily charged at either a flat amount or =
percentage basis in the final bill.
Also analogous to a resort fee, the =E2=80=9Cconsulting fee=E2=80=9D allowe=
d Polar to generate additional cargo revenue by giving the appearance of of=
fering lower rates in comparison to competitors than if Polar had quoted th=
e full (i.e. all costs and fees included) cost.

That is, Polar could advertise low rates, but then tacked on an extra fee f=
or bribes. The complaint includes as an exhibit an email from Polar=E2=80=
=99s vice president of marketing to the owner of Cargo On Demand, saying =
=E2=80=9Cbro here is the updated sheet =E2=80=94=C2=A0pls use this for dist=
ribution=E2=80=9D and attaching an eight-page spreadsheet listing dozens of=
 Polar flights, how much cargo Cargo On Demand had on each flight, and how =
much bribe it owed for each one. =E2=80=9CAs directed, COD then made the sp=
ecified payments for that month via ACH wire transfer.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
The numbers are in the tens or hundreds of dollars per flight, and the enti=
re alleged bribe invoice is for $41,291.93, to be distributed among the non=
descriptly-named entities of several Polar executives. The indictment says =
that Cargo On Demand paid a total of about $1.6 million of kickbacks to Pol=
ar executives from 2016 through 2021, and if you just wrote a check for $1.=
6 million of bribes that would look bad. But sending monthly ACH transfers =
for detailed invoices measured in pennies per kilogram just looks like busi=
ness.=C2=A0
Of course they got arrested anyway; I must emphasize that nothing here is l=
egal advice. Also the owner of Cargo On Demand was himself indicted, for pa=
ying the bribes, which seems a bit harsh. He was dealing with a company, an=
d all the senior executives he dealt with told him that he had to pay these=
 fees! He thought they were a resort fee!

