      AT1s
   =20
 =20

If you are a private wealth manager at a big bank, should you stuff your cl=
ients=E2=80=99 portfolios with leveraged investments in your bank=E2=80=99s=
 own contingent capital securities? I think there=E2=80=99s a good argument=
 for yes:
=09
These securities =E2=80=94 called =E2=80=9Ccontingent convertibles=E2=80=9D=
 (CoCos) and =E2=80=9Cadditional tier 1 capital securities=E2=80=9D (AT1s) =
=E2=80=94=C2=A0look like bonds that pay a high interest rate, but they go t=
o zero if your bank runs into disaster.=C2=A0They are meant to substitute f=
or government bailouts; if the bank becomes insolvent, it gets recapitalize=
d by zeroing the AT1s instead of by relying on a taxpayer bailout.=09Your b=
ank wants to sell these securities, so you are helping out your employer by=
 finding buyers (your clients). The more you sell, the lower your bank=E2=
=80=99s cost of capital, and the higher its profits and your bonus.=09Your =
rich clients want high cash income from securities issued by a big-name ban=
k, so they will enjoy owning these securities, and will be happy with the a=
dvice that you have provided them.=09Unless your bank goes bust, in which c=
ase they will lose all their money =E2=80=94=C2=A0but if your bank goes bus=
t you are probably out of a job anyway, so you don=E2=80=99t care very much=
 about your clients being mad at you in that scenario.

In the state of the world where your bank is fine, these securities are a g=
ood investment for your clients. In the state of the world where your bank =
blows up, these securities are a bad investment for your clients, but that =
is the least of your worries. It=E2=80=99s basically all upside! Load =E2=
=80=99em up with AT1s!
If you are a private wealth manager at a big bank, should you stuff your cl=
ients=E2=80=99 portfolios with the AT1 securities of=C2=A0other=C2=A0big ba=
nks? Some of the same considerations apply, with a bit less force: In a wor=
ld where=C2=A0other=C2=A0big banks go bust, you might be out of a job too, =
since banking crises tend to be pretty contagious. So, sure, load =E2=80=99=
em up.
We are now in the bad state of the world, for Credit Suisse Group AG=E2=80=
=99s AT1 securities, which is awkward for UBS Group AG, which acquired Cred=
it Suisse.  The Wall Street Journal reports:

More than $17 billion of so-called Additional Tier 1 securities issued by C=
redit Suisse became virtually worthless last month, following a controversi=
al decision by Switzerland=E2=80=99s financial regulator. Asian high-net-wo=
rth investors=E2=80=94including clients of Credit Suisse=E2=80=99s own priv=
ate bank=E2=80=94were among the holders of these bonds.
The AT1 bonds were attractive to many wealthy individuals because the secur=
ities offered high returns and were issued by well-known institutions, incl=
uding some of the world=E2=80=99s largest banks. =E2=80=A6
Many private bankers in Asia pushed AT1 bonds from various banks to their c=
lients in recent years, said Jessica Cutrera, Hong Kong-based president of =
independent wealth adviser Leo Wealth.=C2=A0
=E2=80=9CThese AT1s were sold, not bought,=E2=80=9D she said. =E2=80=9CIt w=
as really a yield play. We never liked them, but I know a lot of people who=
 did,=E2=80=9D she added.=C2=A0
Jason Liu, an investor in Taiwan, said he bought two Credit Suisse AT1 bond=
s during the second half of last year at the recommendation of his longtime=
 private banker at UBS. =E2=80=9CI really rely on and trust my banker for h=
is advice,=E2=80=9D he said. =E2=80=A6
The write-down of Credit Suisse=E2=80=99s AT1s adds a potential headache fo=
r UBS executives weighing how to merge the two banks. Credit Suisse=E2=80=
=99s private wealth clients in Asia were a big part of the appeal of the ac=
quisition, the terms of which have left some of those same clients nursing =
losses.=C2=A0

If you were a private wealth adviser at UBS, the acquisition of Credit Suis=
se probably=C2=A0does=C2=A0imperil your job: Presumably there will be some =
overlap among private wealth advisers in Asia at Credit Suisse and UBS, and=
  layoffs are coming. Your clients are mad at you for stuffing them with Cr=
edit Suisse AT1s, but that may not be at the top of your list of problems; =
stuffing them with Credit Suisse AT1s might still have been the right call=
=C2=A0for you personally. But if you are=C2=A0running=C2=A0UBS this does ma=
ke everything more difficult. AT1 investors,=C2=A0as AT1 investors, are the=
re to get zeroed if a bank goes bust; that is their role in the bank=E2=80=
=99s capital structure. But AT1 investors,=C2=A0as clients, are a more deli=
cate matter: If you zero their investment, you can lose them as clients.

