The thing about the Federal Deposit Insurance Corp. is that every once in a=
 while it kicks down the door of a bank on a Friday afternoon, gets rid of =
the bank=E2=80=99s startled=C2=A0managers, and takes over the bank to save =
depositors. This is not the most=C2=A0common=C2=A0activity of the FDIC =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0ideally=C2=A0there are not a lot of bank failures =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0but it is certainly the most=C2=A0dramatic=C2=A0activity of the FDIC, an=
d it is in some sense the=C2=A0core=C2=A0activity of the FDIC; everything e=
lse that it does =E2=80=94=C2=A0regulating banks, running an insurance fund=
 =E2=80=94=C2=A0stems from its ability to show up at a bank and take it ove=
r.
I suppose if you=C2=A0worked at the FDIC you would spend a lot of time prep=
aring for that rare but central event, not only in legal and financial term=
s but also in terms of having a cool line to say when you showed up to seiz=
e a bank. =E2=80=9CThere=E2=80=99s a new sheriff=C2=A0in town=E2=80=9D or w=
hatever, but good. Or you could  whistle =E2=80=9CThe Farmer in the Dell=E2=
=80=9D like Omar in The Wire as terrified bankers fled or put their hands u=
p. That would be cool. Or it wouldn=E2=80=99t be, I mean, possibly the exec=
utives of some failed community bank would not immediately get the referenc=
e and know to be terrified by your whistling, but=C2=A0you=E2=80=99d=C2=A0b=
e pleased with the joke.=C2=A0
Anyway yesterday FDIC Vice Chairman Travis Hill gave a speech about =E2=80=
=9CRecent Bank Failures and the Path Ahead,=E2=80=9D and it is a generally =
useful overview of the recent bank troubles, including the interest rate ri=
sk that community banks took and the speed of modern bank runs. In particul=
ar, he gives a little history of how much faster bank runs have gotten in t=
he modern age:

As the years passed, and technology and communications improved, the nature=
 of bank runs evolved too. In the 1980s, the two largest bank failures were=
 Continental Illinois and First Republic Bank of Dallas.=C2=A0In May 1984, =
Continental Illinois was the victim of what the FDIC described as a =E2=80=
=9Chigh=E2=80=93speed electronic bank run.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0Similar to SVB and=
 Signature, more than 90 percent of its deposits were uninsured.=C2=A0The r=
un lasted for eight days, until federal regulators broke the run by announc=
ing that the FDIC would provide assistance.=C2=A0
Four years later, First Republic Bank of Dallas experienced a similar elect=
ronic run in which corporate depositors, primarily small Texas banks, withd=
rew $1 billion in a single morning.=C2=A0Then=E2=80=93FDIC Chairman Bill Se=
idman described it as =E2=80=9Ca real bank run, even if dressed up in high=
=E2=80=93tech garb.=E2=80=9D
Two decades later, Washington Mutual (WaMu) experienced two =E2=80=9Csilent=
=E2=80=9D deposit runs, the first after the failure of IndyMac in July 2008=
, and a second that took off after the September failure of Lehman Brothers=
. Rather than stand in line at branches, retail customers used ATMs and the=
 internet to withdraw funds.=C2=A0At its peak, WaMu lost $2.8 billion in de=
posits in a single day, a massive figure three times larger than the total =
withdrawals over the 11=E2=80=93day run at IndyMac, yet 15 times smaller th=
an the $42 billion pulled from SVB in one day, and six times smaller than t=
he amount withdrawn from Signature Bank the following day. Game=E2=80=99s t=
he same, just got more fierce.

