<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Bribes</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusine=
ss.com/click/31156532.260450/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2=
FydGljbGVzLzIwMTktMDEtMDQvZG9uLXQtY2FsbC1icmliZXMtY2hpY2tlbnM_Y21waWQ9QkJEM=
DQxMzIzX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXIm=
dXRtX3Rlcm09MjMwNDEzJnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a2=
3cB79922b3e" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blan=
k" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom=
-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; back=
ground-color: #ccc;"> running theme of this column</a>, which is never lega=
l advice, is that if you are going to do bribes you should try to be busine=
sslike about your bribes, instead of being cutesy. Like if you send your co=
lleague a text message saying =E2=80=9Cour =E2=80=98friend=E2=80=99 expects=
 one million =E2=80=98chickens=E2=80=99 for his =E2=80=98help=E2=80=99 with=
 this =E2=80=98contract,=E2=80=99=E2=80=9D that=E2=80=99s gonna look really=
 bad to the jury at your inevitable criminal trial. But if you send a profe=
ssionally formatted=C2=A0invoice saying, like, =E2=80=9CConsulting charges:=
 80 hours @ $1,250 per hour plus 45 basis point success fee on $200 million=
 contract =3D $1,000,000 to be paid by ACH transfer to General Consulting S=
ervices LLC,=E2=80=9D you might still get arrested, but at trial you can sa=
y =E2=80=9Cno that was for consulting, very standard, nothing wrong with th=
at.=E2=80=9D</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Yesterday US prosecutors <a href=3D"https://li=
nk.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/31156532.260450/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuanVzdGl=
jZS5nb3YvdXNhby1zZG55L3ByL3Rlbi1kZWZlbmRhbnRzLWNoYXJnZWQtZGVjYWRlLWxvbmctbX=
VsdGktbWlsbGlvbi1kb2xsYXItc2NoZW1lLWRlZnJhdWQtaW50ZXJuYXRpb25hbA/607f07ceef=
4b8524a319a23cB10c8d037" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" tar=
get=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; b=
order-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style:=
 solid; background-color: #ccc;">brought bribery charges</a> against 10 peo=
ple =E2=80=9Cin connection with a massive scheme to defraud Polar Air Cargo=
 Worldwide, Inc. (=E2=80=98Polar=E2=80=99), a leading cargo airline, of ten=
s of millions of dollars=E2=80=9D with bribes. Polar is a cargo airline =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0a <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/3115=
6532.260450/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuY2gtYXZpYXRpb24uY29tL3BvcnRhbC9uZXdzLzEyMjMxMi1=
1c3MtcG9sYXItYWlyLWNhcmdvLWZhY2VzLXJhY2tldGVlcmluZy1mcmF1ZC1jaGFyZ2VzIzp-On=
RleHQ9UG9sYXIlMjBBaXIlMjBDYXJnbyUyMChQTyUyQyUyME5ldyxvZiUyMGNvbnRyYWN0JTJDJ=
TIwYW5kJTIwdG9ydGlvdXMlMjBpbnRlcmZlcmVuY2U/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB78a8f90=
f" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=
=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: =
1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-c=
olor: #ccc;">joint venture</a> of DHL and Atlas Air =E2=80=94=C2=A0that sol=
d cargo space to shippers, and if you wanted cargo space on Polar you alleg=
edly had to pay (1) Polar the rates that it charged you plus (2) some bribe=
s to the Polar executives who were selling you the space.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The executives included Polar=E2=80=99s chief =
operating officer, its vice president of marketing,=C2=A0its vice president=
 of operations and its senior director of customer service. =E2=80=9CIn gen=
eral,=E2=80=9D <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/311=
56532.260450/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuanVzdGljZS5nb3YvdXNhby1zZG55L3ByZXNzLXJlbGVhc2=
UvZmlsZS8xNTc5MjcxL2Rvd25sb2Fk/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB1839dff6" itemprop=
=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #0=
00000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-b=
ottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">=
says the indictment</a>,=C2=A0=E2=80=9Cthe=C2=A0Executive Defendants often =
had the ability to propose vendors, to advocate on behalf of certain vendor=
s or customers, and to exercise significant influence over both Polar's sel=
ection of vendors and the rates offered to its customers.=E2=80=9D They wer=
e the people selling space on Polar=E2=80=99s planes, and so they could set=
 the rates for that space =E2=80=94=C2=A0and the rates they set, allegedly,=
 included both a payment to Polar and a payment to themselves.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But it was all <em>businesslike</em>. From the=
 indictment:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">To conceal the kickbacks and conflicted owners=
hip interests from Polar, and thereby to continue the fraud scheme, [they]=
=C2=A0often directed the kickbacks and ownership distributions be paid to l=
imited liability companies with non-descript names that were, in fact, cont=
rolled by the Executive Defendants. =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">From in or about 2009 through in or about July=
 2021, Polar contracted with freight forwarders to sell available cargo spa=
ce on behalf of downstream shipping customers, who, in turn, paid freight f=
orwarders to secure cargo space and coordinate logistics. ... These kickbac=
ks were typically calculated based on how many kilograms of cargo the freig=
ht forwarders had shipped with Polar during a particular period. At no poin=
t before the discovery of the fraud in or about July 2021 were the kickback=
s from freight forwarders known to Polar.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CAt no point =E2=80=A6=C2=A0were the k=
ickbacks from freight forwarders known to Polar=E2=80=9D is a weird sentenc=
e. Polar is not a person; it has no consciousness. The kickbacks were not k=
nown to Polar=E2=80=99s=C2=A0<em>owners</em>, I assume, or perhaps to its c=
hief executive officer. But they were known to its chief operating officer,=
 because he was allegedly receiving them. This was not some rogue salespers=
on taking bribes; this was a big chunk of the executive team.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And so there is an <a href=3D"https://link.mai=
l.bloombergbusiness.com/click/31156532.260450/aHR0cHM6Ly9hc3NldHMuYndieC5pb=
y9kb2N1bWVudHMvdXNlcnMvaXFqV0hCRmRmeElVL3JlNVBkcG55RmpYYy92MA/607f07ceef4b8=
524a319a23cB20235500" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=
=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bord=
er-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: so=
lid; background-color: #ccc;">amazing civil lawsuit</a> filed late last yea=
r by one of the customers, Cargo On Demand Inc., against Polar, complaining=
 that Polar charged it bribes. Cargo On Demand=E2=80=99s point was, look, i=
f Polar=E2=80=99s salespeople and senior managers told it to pay these fees=
 as part of the price of cargo, it had to pay those fees. From the complain=
t:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">COD entered into the [Blokced Space Agreement]=
 with Polar primarily because Polar=E2=80=99s rates on the specific air rou=
tes relevant to COD=E2=80=99s customers were typically lower than the rates=
 quoted to COD by any other airlines providing service on the same routes.<=
/p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">However, in order to actually utilize its carg=
o space allotment, COD was advised by members of Polar Management that it w=
as required to also pay Polar (via Polar Management), and certain third-par=
ty consulting companies connected to Polar, additional =E2=80=9Cconsulting =
fees=E2=80=9D separate and apart from the BSA.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">These consulting fees were charged beginning a=
t the inception of COD=E2=80=99s relationship with Polar in 2014. =E2=80=A6=
</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The consulting fees were calculated based on t=
he monthly tonnage for all goods that COD shipped with Polar. The amount of=
 the fee typically varied between $0.25-$0.50 per kilo of tonnage, in addit=
ion to the agreed BSA rates.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The consulting fee requirement was articulated=
 to COD by multiple members of Polar Management (which included, without li=
mitation, the company=E2=80=99s Chief Operating Officer and multiple vice p=
residents and directors) over the course of seven years. =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">COD was advised and instructed by Polar Manage=
ment that these additional =E2=80=9Cconsulting fees=E2=80=9D were part of P=
olar=E2=80=99s regular way of doing business with all customers that had an=
nual BSA contracts with Polar.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">To COD, such fees seemed akin to a hotel =E2=
=80=9Cresort fee=E2=80=9D. In other words, a mandatory fee that is not incl=
uded (or not prominently included) in the quoted rate, yet mandatorily char=
ged at either a flat amount or percentage basis in the final bill.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Also analogous to a resort fee, the =E2=80=9Cc=
onsulting fee=E2=80=9D allowed Polar to generate additional cargo revenue b=
y giving the appearance of offering lower rates in comparison to competitor=
s than if Polar had quoted the full (i.e. all costs and fees included) cost=
.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">That is, Polar could advertise low rates, but =
then tacked on an extra fee for bribes. The complaint <a href=3D"https://li=
nk.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/31156532.260450/aHR0cHM6Ly9hc3NldHMuYnd=
ieC5pby9kb2N1bWVudHMvdXNlcnMvaXFqV0hCRmRmeElVL3I0YmZTaHJqeDh5cy92MA/607f07c=
eef4b8524a319a23cBe08e8024" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" =
target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important=
; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-sty=
le: solid; background-color: #ccc;">includes as an exhibit</a> an email fro=
m Polar=E2=80=99s vice president of marketing to the owner of Cargo On Dema=
nd, saying =E2=80=9Cbro here is the updated sheet =E2=80=94=C2=A0pls use th=
is for distribution=E2=80=9D and attaching an eight-page spreadsheet listin=
g dozens of Polar flights, how much cargo Cargo On Demand had on each fligh=
t, and how much bribe it owed for each one. =E2=80=9CAs directed, COD then =
made the specified payments for that month via ACH wire transfer.=E2=80=9D=
=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The numbers are in the tens or hundreds of dol=
lars per flight, and the entire alleged bribe invoice is for $41,291.93, to=
 be distributed among the nondescriptly-named entities of several Polar exe=
cutives. The indictment says that Cargo On Demand paid a total of about $1.=
6 million of kickbacks to Polar executives from 2016 through 2021, and if y=
ou just wrote a check for $1.6 million of bribes that would look bad. But s=
ending monthly ACH transfers for detailed invoices measured in pennies per =
kilogram just looks like business.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Of course they got arrested anyway; I must emp=
hasize that nothing here is legal advice. Also the owner of Cargo On Demand=
 was himself indicted, for paying the bribes, which seems a bit harsh. He w=
as dealing with a company, and all the senior executives he dealt with told=
 him that he had to pay these fees! He thought they were a resort fee!</p>
<table class=3D"header" width=3D"100%" border=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"0" cellp=
adding=3D"0">
<tr>
<td class=3D"body-header-container" style=3D"border-collapse: collapse; mso=
-table-lspace: 0pt; mso-table-rspace: 0pt;">
<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">AT1s</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If you are a private wealth manager at a big b=
ank, should you stuff your clients=E2=80=99 portfolios with leveraged inves=
tments in your bank=E2=80=99s own contingent capital securities? I think th=
ere=E2=80=99s a good argument for yes:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">
<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/31156532.260450/aH=
R0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDMtMjAvdWJzL=
WdvdC1jcmVkaXQtc3Vpc3NlLWZvci1hbG1vc3Qtbm90aGluZz9jbXBpZD1CQkQwNDEzMjNfTU9O=
RVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0=
yMzA0MTMmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBe9c942b4"=
 itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"=
color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px;=
 border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color=
: #ccc;">These securities</a> =E2=80=94 called =E2=80=9Ccontingent converti=
bles=E2=80=9D (CoCos) and =E2=80=9Cadditional tier 1 capital securities=E2=
=80=9D (AT1s) =E2=80=94=C2=A0look like bonds that pay a high interest rate,=
 but they go to zero if your bank runs into disaster.=C2=A0They are meant t=
o substitute for government bailouts; if the bank becomes insolvent, it get=
s recapitalized by zeroing the AT1s instead of by relying on a taxpayer bai=
lout.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Your bank wants to sell thes=
e securities, so you are helping out your employer by finding buyers (your =
clients). The more you sell, the lower your bank=E2=80=99s cost of capital,=
 and the higher its profits and your bonus.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bott=
om: 5px;">Your rich clients want high cash income from securities issued by=
 a big-name bank, so they will enjoy owning these securities, and will be h=
appy with the advice that you have provided them.</li>=09<li style=3D"margi=
n-bottom: 5px;">Unless your bank goes bust, in which case they will lose al=
l their money =E2=80=94=C2=A0but if your bank goes bust you are probably ou=
t of a job anyway, so you don=E2=80=99t care very much about your clients b=
eing mad at you in that scenario.</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In the state of the world where your bank is f=
ine, these securities are a good investment for your clients. In the state =
of the world where your bank blows up, these securities are a bad investmen=
t for your clients, but that is the least of your worries. It=E2=80=99s bas=
ically all upside! Load =E2=80=99em up with AT1s!</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If you are a private wealth manager at a big b=
ank, should you stuff your clients=E2=80=99 portfolios with the AT1 securit=
ies of=C2=A0<em>other=C2=A0</em>big banks? Some of the same considerations =
apply, with a bit less force: In a world where=C2=A0<em>other=C2=A0</em>big=
 banks go bust, you might be out of a job too, since banking crises tend to=
 be pretty contagious. So, sure, load =E2=80=99em up.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">We are now in the bad state of the world, for =
Credit Suisse Group AG=E2=80=99s AT1 securities, which is awkward for UBS G=
roup AG, which acquired Credit Suisse. <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombe=
rgbusiness.com/click/31156532.260450/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cud3NqLmNvbS9hcnRpY2xlcy=
9jcmVkaXQtc3Vpc3Nlcy1yaXNreS1ib25kLXdpcGVvdXQtaHVydHMtYXNpYXMtcmljaC1hNTAyY=
2U_bW9kPWl0cF93c2omcnU9eWFob28/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB9b673c32" itemprop=
=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #0=
00000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-b=
ottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">=
 The Wall Street Journal reports</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">More than $17 billion of so-called Additional =
Tier 1 securities issued by Credit Suisse became virtually worthless last m=
onth, following a controversial decision by Switzerland=E2=80=99s financial=
 regulator. Asian high-net-worth investors=E2=80=94including clients of Cre=
dit Suisse=E2=80=99s own private bank=E2=80=94were among the holders of the=
se bonds.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The AT1 bonds were attractive to many wealthy =
individuals because the securities offered high returns and were issued by =
well-known institutions, including some of the world=E2=80=99s largest bank=
s. =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Many private bankers in Asia pushed AT1 bonds =
from various banks to their clients in recent years, said Jessica Cutrera, =
Hong Kong-based president of independent wealth adviser Leo Wealth.=C2=A0</=
p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CThese AT1s were sold, not bought,=E2=
=80=9D she said. =E2=80=9CIt was really a yield play. We never liked them, =
but I know a lot of people who did,=E2=80=9D she added.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Jason Liu, an investor in Taiwan, said he boug=
ht two Credit Suisse AT1 bonds during the second half of last year at the r=
ecommendation of his longtime private banker at UBS. =E2=80=9CI really rely=
 on and trust my banker for his advice,=E2=80=9D he said. =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The write-down of Credit Suisse=E2=80=99s AT1s=
 adds a potential headache for UBS executives weighing how to merge the two=
